    <article id="12-feb-2015">
        <div>12 Feb 2015</div>
        <h4>My fourth learning Log entry</h4>
        <section>
            <h5>Notes</h5>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    We, as a class, saw different websites about randomness. During the show and tell, there was an interaction between the user and the interface. You use the mouse to slap man with an eel. Professor Benson showed us with a drawing as well as an explanation on how this interaction can be done. We also looked at different people's learning logs, so we can see what can be improved for the future. And also see what we are going to learn. We learned about the graphic design of the website so that it can be easily used by the user. There should be no problem with the user using. Becuase the user has a problem, the user went onto this website, so he or she can solve that problem. Our job is to help the user reach that goal. We looked at the cookie recipe and made many boxes. Our job is to re-create the cookie recipe ourselves.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h5>Reading Response</h5>
            <h6>
                <a href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2011/06/22/following-a-web-design-process.html" target="_blank">Following a Web Design Process</a>.
            </h6>
            <h6>
                <a href="https://files.acrobat.com/a/preview/3cd937ef-bdc1-4790-b620-b2791e86a4ef.pdf" target="_blank">How to Read a Wireframe</a>.
            </h6>
            <h6>
                <a href="http://www.alistapart.com/article/semanticsinhtml5.html" target="_blank">Semantics in HTML5</a>.
            </h6>
            <p>I found the article about following a Web Design Process interesting. Because I am taking the class Ideation and Prototyping, this process reminds me about all the important aspects to designing anything for the user. It must be easy to use, greet the user, interact with the user, and make the user feel like the web is  person. The steps in this article are Planning, Design, Development, Launch, and then Post Launch. However, in Ideation and Prototyping class, there are four steps. Those steps are ideate (Planning), Build (Design and development), Test (Launch), and then instead of Post Launch, it is reiterate. It helps me to remind myself, "Is the user comfortable? Does this web interact friendly with the user?" These are the things to think about while developing a web.</p>
        </section>

    </article>

